        <body>
            <pb n="1R"/>
            <p rend="align(center)">
                <placeName>Richmond</placeName>
                <date>June 10<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 1829</date>
            </p>
            <p>
                <addressee>Raphael de Cordova Esq</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">
                <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Your letter of the <date>31st May</date> came to hand on the
                first<lb/> day of <date>Sebuot</date>, I hasten to communicate the result of my
                enquiry in relation<lb/> to its contents. <persName>Mr Isaac Leezer</persName> a
                young gentleman who has resided a few<lb/> years among us, I can confidently
                recommend as a person of steady habits,<lb/> of moral worth, a strict observer of
                our religious rites, possessing a cultivated<lb/> mind, capable of instructing your
                children in Hebrew and with a little practice<lb/> will be enabled to discharge the
                duties of Hazan—our holy language is perfect<lb/>ly familiar to him, he renders
                Hebrew into English and <sic>english</sic> into Hebrew,<lb/> with great facility and
                possesses a grammatical knowledge of both, he pronoun_<lb/>ces agreeably to the
                    <add>ספרדים</add> mode extremely well and knows the <add>טעמים</add> in
                reading<lb/> the <add>ספר</add> and <add>הפטרות</add>, with attention and experience
                the pronunciation will soon be<lb/> perfect, he has a passable voice, but will
                require some instruction in the festival<lb/> tunes. <persName>Mr
                    Peixotto</persName> has kindly offered to instruct him, that gentleman has
                conver<lb/>sed with him on the subject. <persName>Mr L.</persName> is extremely
                diffident of his powers to<lb/> give satisfaction as a reader but <del>take him all
                    in all</del> is willing to make an expe<lb/>riment. I have no hesitation in
                saying, take him all in all that he will<lb/> be a valuable acquisition to any
                congregation, he combines the qualifications of an<lb/> instructor and an exposer of
                our laws and customs, possesses a decent classical<lb/> knowledge, composes with
                facility and correctness, has an extensive historical<lb/> knowledge and is a
                    bell<add>?</add> letters scholar.__his pecuniary circumstances are<lb/>
                perfectly easy and his relative &amp; patron<add>?</add> is able to make him in some
                degree in-<lb/>dependent of seeking office as a means of support, those observations
                proceed<lb/> from myself and are not intended to influence your decision in relation
                to his compen<lb/>sation__I shall be glad to know that he is placed in a situation
                that will render<lb/> him useful to his religious community, tho' young, he is
                sedate, and with in-<lb/>creasing years and his love of learning, and pious <hi
                    rend="underline">conviction</hi> of the truths of<lb/> the Religion he professes
                he will if blessed with length of days become a<lb/> shining light in
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName>—</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">Should you be inclined to view these <sic>characteristicks</sic>
                favourably<lb/> I have no fears on the score of responsibility I this incur, any
                further<lb/> communications in relation to this business will I presume be
                addressed<lb/> to <persName>Mr L</persName>_The congregation in this place is
                designated <add>ק"ק בית שלום</add><lb/> Permit me to make you the medium of a
                communication to the Parnass of your</p>
            <pb n="1V"/>
            <p>respectable congregation and request the favour of adding my family name to the
                record<lb/> which is kept of the early contributors to the Old Synagogue; my name
                    <add>יעקב בר משה</add> will<lb/> be found among the purchasers of the corner
                stones of that building, of the four purchasers<lb/> I alone survive. I wish the
                name to stand <add>יעקב בר משה מרדכי</add> I presume there will<lb/> be no objection
                in thus gratifying a native of your city and one far advanced in<lb/> years__ If I
                can be useful to the Committee please command my<lb/> best services</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">With great Respect</p>
            <p rend="indent(4)">your very obt svt</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">
                <persName role="author">Jacob Mordecai</persName>
            </p>
        </body>
